[{"id":"VR871114","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">In the standing-wave model for an electron in a circular orbit around a nucleus, the orbit’s circumference must be an integer multiple of the electron’s de Broglie wavelength. In each of three different systems <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Z\"><math alttext=\"Z\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Z</mtext></math></span></span>, a single electron is modeled as being in a circular orbit around a nucleus. The three systems are described as follows.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">• In system <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span>, an electron orbits a hydrogen nucleus <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H with mass number 1 and atomic number 1\"><math alttext=\"H with mass number 1 and atomic number 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>(</mo><mmultiscripts><mtext>H</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mmultiscripts><mo>)</mo></math></span></span> in the ground state (smallest orbit possible).</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">• In system <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span>, an electron orbits a helium nucleus <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H e with mass number 4 and atomic number 2\"><math alttext=\"H e with mass number 4 and atomic number 2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mo>(</mo><mmultiscripts><mtext>He</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>2</mn><mn>4</mn></mmultiscripts><mo>)</mo></mstyle></math></span></span> in the ground state (smallest orbit possible).</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">• In system <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Z\"><math alttext=\"Z\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Z</mtext></math></span></span>, an electron orbits a hydrogen nucleus <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"H with mass number 1 and atomic number 1\"><math alttext=\"H with mass number 1 and atomic number 1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>(</mo><mmultiscripts><mtext>H</mtext><mprescripts></mprescripts><mn>1</mn><mn>1</mn></mmultiscripts><mo>)</mo></math></span></span> in the second-smallest orbit possible.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following correctly ranks the number <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n\"><math alttext=\"n\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>n</mi></math></span></span> of de Broglie wavelengths that fit around the circumferences of the electrons’ orbits in systems <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X\"><math alttext=\"X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>X</mtext></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y\"><math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Y</mtext></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Z\"><math alttext=\"Z\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Z</mtext></math></span></span>?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR871114_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"n sub Y is greater than, n sub Z, which is greater than n sub X\"><math alttext=\"n sub Y is greater than, n sub Z, which is greater than n sub X\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>Y</mtext></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>Z</mtext></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>n</mi><mtext>X</mtext></msub></math></span></spa